In his life a noble example of what our breed can produce, of what energy‚ honesty, intensity, and genius can achieve3 and in his death a terrible example of that revenge which the body takes upon the soul when brought to hay by its inexorable tasknraster. I need say no more. His story is more tragic than any tragedy. Would to God it may warn those who come after to be wise in time, to take the same—I ask no inore—care of their body, which is their servant, their beast of burden, as they would of their horse.
